GitHub → Jenkins → EC2 (File Sync Project)
•	You update a file in GitHub
•	Jenkins pulls the latest code
•	Jenkins copies the file to EC2
•	EC2 file content gets updated
________________________________________
 STEP 1: GitHub Repository Setup
Create / update your GitHub repo like this:
ec2-folder-automation/
 ├── Jenkinsfile
 └── hello_world.txt
hello_world.txt (GitHub)
Hello from GitHub – Version 1
Commit & push.
________________________________________
STEP 2: Jenkinsfile (IMPORTANT)
This pipeline:
•	pulls GitHub code
•	copies file to EC2
•	overwrites file in /opt
pipeline {
    agent any

    stages {
        stage('Clone Repo') {
            steps {
                git branch: 'main',
                    url: 'https://github.com/sowtheswari22/ec2-folder-automation.git'
            }
        }

        stage('Deploy File to EC2') {
            steps {
                sshagent(['ec2-key']) {
                    sh """
                    scp -o StrictHostKeyChecking=no hello_world.txt ubuntu@<EC2_PUBLIC_IP>:/opt/hello_world.txt
                    """
                }
            }
        }
    }
}
Replace:
•	<EC2_PUBLIC_IP> with your EC2 public IP
•	ec2-key → Jenkins credential ID
Commit this Jenkinsfile.
________________________________________
 STEP 3: Jenkins Job Configuration
1.	Jenkins → New Item
2.	Name: github-to-ec2
3.	Type: Pipeline
4.	Definition: Pipeline script from SCM
5.	SCM: Git
6.	Repo URL:
7.	https://github.com/sowtheswari22/ec2-folder-automation.git
8.	Branch: main
9.	Script Path: Jenkinsfile
10.	Save
________________________________________
STEP 4: Build & Verify
Build Jenkins job
Click Build Now
Login to EC2
cat /opt/hello_world.txt
Output:
Hello from GitHub – Version 1
 Success!
________________________________________
 STEP 5: Change File in GitHub (TEST)
Edit hello_world.txt in GitHub:
Hello from GitHub – Version 2
Commit & push.
 Click Build Now again.
Check EC2:
cat /opt/hello_world.txt
Output:
Hello from GitHub – Version 2
GitHub changes reflected in server
